<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus verrucosus </i>(a CNPS 2.2 list plant) is an upright shrub with warty stems; its leaves are evergreen and alternate. The species is restricted to San Diego Co. and adjacent northwestern Baja California. It is a characteristic species of southern maritime chaparral (Holland 1986, Hogan et al. 1996, see the discussion in the Changes Since the First Edition section). It is ecologically similar to <i>Ceanothus megacarpus, </i>and hybrids have been observed in coastal Orange Co. (F. Roberts 1994 pers. comm.). <br/>
<br/>
As an obligate-seeding species, <i>C. verrucosus </i>has a persistent seed bank, and stands of almost pure ceanothus grow rapidly and dominate a few years following fire. These stands tend to senesce and transition to other types following several decades without fire (Keeley and Davis 2007) such as stands of <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum-Xylococcus bicolor </i>alliance. Currently, we are treating <i>Ceanothus verrucosus </i>alliance as a separate temporal entity where periodic fire disturbance is a driving factor, as in the <i>Lotus scoparius </i>and <i>Malacothamnus fasciculatus </i>alliances. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The alliance description comes from surveys in San Diego Co. on steep northerly or neutral slopes around and west of Lake Hodges where <i>Ceanothus verrucosus-Xylococcus bicolor</i> association is described (Evens and San 2005). Additional transect sampling verifies the dominance of <i>Ceanothus verrucosus</i> in San Diego Co. (CVIS 1995) from Coastal Terraces and Coastal Hills (261Bi-Bj) subsections. Taylor (2004) analyzed old Vegetation Type Map (VTM) samples in San Diego Co. and found that <i>Eriodictyon crassifolium</i> and <i>Ceanothus verrucosus</i> dominated a group of related plots, the only group in the study lacking a statistically significant preference for any factor studied other than fire. He hypothesized that this group’s distribution was closely tied to recent site history. It is likely that all these stands sampled had burned within 1-3 decades of sampling. We need further sampling and monitoring of post-fire stands to decide whether these stands should stay as a separate alliance or as discrete associations of the <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum— Xylococcus bicolor</i> alliance. </div>
</div>

	

    
